  "chunk_index": 21,
  "summary": "After Tora Grey expresses sadness regarding Mrs. Clarke's dislike of her, she departs. Poirot observes that Tora is both brave and cunning, noting her fashionable attire. He also experiences a vague, nagging impression that he and Hastings had previously shared a meaningful conversation, though he cannot recall the details.\n\nPoirot and Hastings later visit Kempthorpe to see Mrs. Clarke. They are met by Nurse Capstick, who explains that while Mrs. Clarke is receiving new therapy, her condition remains poor. Capstick notes that Mrs. Clarke and her late husband, Carl, were a very happy couple. She mentions that after Carl's death, Sir Carmichael took up collecting as a consolation and worked with Tora Grey to re-catalog the museum before Tora eventually left due to Mrs. Clarke's declining health.\n\nIn a second-floor living room, Poirot and Hastings find Mrs. Clarke in a dazed, physically weakened state, appearing to be under the influence of drugs that make time feel stagnant. Mrs. Clarke discusses Carl’s excellent physical fitness and expresses concern that Franklin Clarke is impulsive and easily led astray. When the topic of Carl's death arises, Mrs. Clarke asserts that the murderer must have been around the house that day. When Poirot mentions that the servants and Tora Grey claimed no strangers visited the house, Mrs. Clarke becomes agitated and calls Tora a liar. She reveals a deep animosity toward Tora, claiming Carl was overly sympathetic to her status as an orphan. Mrs. Clarke further discloses that she used her illness to pressure Franklin into paying Tora three months' salary to ensure she would leave the house immediately.",
